<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}-{5}{y}={4}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle-{9}{x}+{6}{y}={3}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left(-{1},-{1}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of --9. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle--\frac{{9}}{{1}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{-{9}}}{{1}}{\left({1}{x}+-{5}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{-{9}}}{{1}}{\left({4}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left(-{9}\right)}{x}+-{45}{y}={36}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{9}{x}+{6}{y}={3}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{39}{y}={39}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=\frac{{39}}{{-{{39}}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=-{1}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+-{5}{\left(-{1}\right)}={4}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}+{\left({5}\right)}={4}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}={4}-{\left({5}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1}{x}=-{1}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-\frac{{1}}{{1}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=-{1}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left(-{1},-{1}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

